comments: I accidentally clicked on the last attention check.  I tried to undo it but it wouldn't let me.  I'm very sorry about that.

Most of the study I answered the way I did because for me, if I'm in a situation where I get to save someone and a criminal is hurt, I would rather do it with an object than by my hands. I think I would feel less guilt/be more opt to help save that person.
God bless and good luck! All clear.
This was a very interesting survey.
I accidentally clicked the button next to the first reading carefully answer and it wouldn't let me uncheck it
No, but thanks for the HIT!  I did my best and hope the data is useful!
Yes, I saw both the attention checks that said do not select anything. But, I accidentally selected them and could not unselect them.
No. Thank you for including this field though!

I feel like a lot of the initial questions were very situational.  I think there's a difference between self defense and a purely hypothetical situation where the "harm" is fully separated from the situation.  Also, I apologize as my first answers are a bit all over the place, I got confused about the negative and positive sides, and said I felt moderately negative and positive..
I accidentally clicked on the first attention test question and could not undo it
I clicked "strongly agree" on the question that said "all people should skip this to show their attention/alertness", then i realized i was suppose to skip it, but did not know how to go back.
Thank you for allowing my participation!
there was one question that said to skip and i mis clicked with my mouse and could no de-select. I did read through and recognize this.
i'm not positive if I did the first part correct, I was a little bit confused.
This was a well designed and interesting study.
All of these questions take in a lot of factors so it was very difficult to answer some of them.
I accidentally clicked "strongly agree" on one of the questions where we were asked to skip to check for attentiveness.
Accidentally read the last question and clicked even though it said to skip.

I accidentally selected a question that was an attention check.  The text was "I am reading carefully and will not answer this one" I selected the far left option which i believe was strongly disagree since i could not deselect it. sorry for the trouble thanks
I really like the questions that you tried to explore which give me many thoughts and introspections about human.
When you said "get high" you didn't mention in what way so it's hard to answer.
Everything in the study was very clear and straightforward. Thank you so much for the opportunity to participate and best of luck with your research :)

I'm not sure I understood the first set of questions.  When you say "is it okay to break a criminals legs in order to save one person?"  Are you asking that as you're speaking in the moment of a crime or in general?  Like, if I see someone beating my brother and I save my brother by breaking the guys legs, I totally support that.  But, if you're asking that in general, if this person is a criminal, an average person should just break his legs?  No, leave dealing with criminals to law enforcement.
no other then the one question i clicked too fast and couldn't unclick it even though it says not to click anything
I wish I was able to go back to the first instruction page because I was unsure if i was answering whether it was morally wrong or just the wrong way to stop  the criminal.

The beginning part could have been a bit more descriptive, like what type of situation was taking place (robbery, breaking & entering, etc.), and also whether the criminal had a weapon on them. Personally, I kept imagining a hostage situation where the criminal had a knife/gun on them, and that may have interfered with the decisions I made compared to what others may had chosen.
I enjoyed this study. Thank you for your time!
Don't make people leave questions blank as attention checks. They might accidentally click and then cannot unclick. It's unfair.
I accidentally clicked one of the attention checks. I use arrows and tab to answer surveys so I mess up. Hope you can approve. Thank you
i didn't entire understand the first part when i had to respond with "i feel positively/negatively with my response", when i was saying if doing something to a criminals was good or bad.

When changing my answer to another question, I accidentally clicked on an option on the second bubble attention check. I tried to complete this honestly and hope this won't cause a problem. Again, I apologize.

I accidentally hit the answer of question "I am reading carefully and will not answer this one" when I was choosing the answer for the next question. I just hope this will not influence the data collection. And it would be nice if participants can repeal the answer. Thank you!
Please don't do the "Don't answer this question" type questions. All it takes is one momentary lapse of focus and you're screwed. Or, at least you have to explain to the requester.
My answers for some of these scenarios would change based on circumstances. I feel that some of these actions are right only if reactionary/in the heat of the moment.
I accidentally clicked one attention check. Entirely my fault. Sorry!

I'm not even religious and I can't believe that anyone would accept any of those scenarios as acceptable to save a live. I can't imagine someone like Jesus saying: "Hey you know what, let's hurt that criminal to save that kid". It was extremely shocking for me to realize that some human beuing would think that hurting a criminal is acceptable in ANY way. It was hard to order those at as better than others as they were all equally bad in my book. Thanks for the experience, if anything it shows me I'm not willing to go to extreme to save a life. All life is precious, even the life of a criminal.

I saw the question about not clicking if you're paying attention, but like most people that take surveys, instinct kicked in and I selected a button before it was too late. I was paying attention, my data is good, and those types of attention checks are terrible for people that read quickly.
